      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, no need to apologize! The goblin was just trying to explain that sometimes you have to let go of things that aren't worth the effort to keep, much like how we subtract the salvage value.\n\nSalvage value is essentially the estimated amount of money you will get when you finally sell or scrap that heavy machinery at the end of its useful life. Think of it as the \"goblin's leftover stash\" at the end of the game; it's the value you still have left after the main adventure is over.\n\nWe subtract it from the cost because accounting wants to show you only the *actual* loss in value during the machine's working life. If you didn't subtract it, you'd be pretending the machine is worth zero when you sell it, which would be like telling a goblin that the gold coin they found in the wall is worthless just because they didn't spend enough time polishing it.\n\nBy subtracting the $5,000 salvage value from the $50,000 cost, we are saying, \"Okay, we know we'll get $5,000 back at the end, so we only need to account for the $45,000 that",
